09:19.492 --> 09:21.394 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
big brush and say, oh, they're
all terrorists.

09:21.428 --> 09:25.532 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I think it's going to be
very hard, given
the corrosive mistrust between
the two governments.

09:25.565 --> 09:28.701 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's basically no trust left
between the
national security establishment,
the career

09:28.735 --> 09:32.806 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
people who will be serving under
a president-elect
Trump and their Russian
counterparts.

09:32.839 --> 09:37.210 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It is going to be very hard to
build that
trust out of the barren
landscape that they're

09:37.243 --> 09:38.878 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
inheriting.

09:38.912 --> 09:42.048 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: What does that
win in Syria
or ISIL, what is the cost of
that?

09:42.081 --> 09:43.049 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Is it Crimea?

09:43.082 --> 09:44.050 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Is it Ukraine?

09:44.083 --> 09:45.885 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ANDREW WEISS: We don't know.

09:45.919 --> 09:48.455 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so far the price that
Russians have been
talking about in their
communications with

09:48.488 --> 09:49.989 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the United States are
exorbitant.

09:50.023 --> 09:53.560 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They're saying the United States
should recognize
the annexation of Crimea.

09:53.593 --> 09:57.263 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They're saying the United States
should pay
a penalty for the imposition of
economic sanctions

09:57.297 --> 10:01.935 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
after the shoot-down of a
civilian airliner
over Eastern Ukraine in July
2014.

10:01.968 --> 10:03.736 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
These are outlandish demands.

10:03.770 --> 10:07.106 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think it would be unusual
to expect
that the Trump administration is
somehow going

10:07.140 --> 10:08.942 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to grant those wishes.

10:08.975 --> 10:14.047 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Are there
concerns that
the Trump administration doesn't
see the multiple

10:14.080 --> 10:15.515 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
dimensions of Vladimir Putin?

10:15.548 --> 10:17.517 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ANDREW WEISS: Well, I think we
just don't
know.

10:17.550 --> 10:21.321 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
We know that this is a
president-elect who
has very little foreign policy
experience.

10:21.354 --> 10:25.925 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's tapped a neophyte to be his
secretary
of state, Rex Tillerson.

10:25.959 --> 10:28.294 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
These are people who have
records in the business
community.

10:28.328 --> 10:31.097 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They have got I think a lot of
credentials
in that area.

10:31.130 --> 10:35.001 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But for the issues that have
been at the heart
of U.S.-Russian relations over
the past two-and-a-half

10:35.034 --> 10:39.339 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
decades and which have created
so mention
tension and so much built-up
resentment and

10:39.372 --> 10:41.674 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
mistrust, it's not something
that they have
really had to deal with.

10:41.708 --> 10:43.710 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: You called Rex
Tillerson
a neophyte.

10:43.743 --> 10:46.846 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's a neophyte to government,
but not necessarily
to foreign affairs.

10:46.880 --> 10:50.517 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Technically, he might be the
person with the
most connections to Russia in
the Trump administration.

10:50.550 --> 10:55.688 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANDREW WEISS: There's no doubt
that Rex Tillerson's
access and accomplishments in
Russia are dramatic.

10:55.722 --> 11:01.227 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's come from a period of
working in Russia
at the highest levels going back
to the late

11:01.261 --> 11:02.228 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
1990s.

11:02.262 --> 11:03.229 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He knows Putin personally.

11:03.263 --> 11:04.931 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He knows Putin's top advisers
personally.

11:04.964 --> 11:06.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's all obviously a real
asset.

11:06.766 --> 11:10.303 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The question is, does he know a
lot about
the IMF treaty, does he know a
lot about the

11:10.336 --> 11:13.806 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
harassment of U.S. diplomatic
personnel, does
he follow Syria closely?

11:13.840 --> 11:17.477 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My sense is those are issues
that he has not
had to delve into in great
detail.

11:17.510 --> 11:20.680 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Andrew Weiss
from the Carnegie
Endowment for International
Peace, thanks

11:20.713 --> 11:21.681 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for joining us.

11:21.714 --> 11:25.852 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ANDREW WEISS: Thank you.

11:25.885 --> 11:36.462 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Next to the
analysis of
Brooks and Corn.

11:36.496 --> 11:39.465 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's syndicated New York Times
columnist
David Brooks, and "Mother Jones"
Washington

11:39.499 --> 11:41.234 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
bureau chief David Corn.

11:41.267 --> 11:45.171 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
All right, David Brooks, let's
start some
of the unilateral steps that
President Obama

11:45.204 --> 11:47.140 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
has taken just in the last few
weeks.

11:47.173 --> 11:52.078 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We are talking about everything
from the Russian
sanctions to the U.N. Security
Council condemnation

11:52.111 --> 11:56.182 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- or allowing the U.N. Security
Council to
go forward in the condemnation
of the Israeli

11:56.215 --> 11:58.017 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
settlements, preserving large
swathes of land.

11:58.051 --> 12:01.788 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As the paper of record, The New
York Times,
said, is this about boxing Trump
in?

12:01.821 --> 12:03.156 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: I guess a little.

12:03.189 --> 12:05.558 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But what can be done by a
president can be
undone by a president.

12:05.592 --> 12:09.195 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What's sort of remarkable is
that, especially
in the Israel and the Russia
cases, you have

12:09.228 --> 12:14.434 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
got a U.S. citizen, Donald
Trump, siding with
a foreign leader against the
U.S. president.

12:14.467 --> 12:19.405 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
There is a reason why
president-elects have
tried to remain mute during
their transitional

12:19.439 --> 12:23.242 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
periods, relatively, because you
just don't
want to be for somebody -- some
other country

12:23.276 --> 12:26.679 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
against your own government, and
especially
when you're about to take the
helm of that

12:26.713 --> 12:28.481 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
government.

12:28.514 --> 12:31.317 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there will be a lot of
permanent people
who are just going to be stuck
there who are

12:31.351 --> 12:34.420 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
now in a war between the
president-elect and
the guy they're currently
serving.

12:34.454 --> 12:37.223 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: David Corn,
does this violate
the spirit of that smooth
transition that

12:37.256 --> 12:40.860 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
both gentlemen had that photo-op
in the White
House?

12:40.893 --> 12:44.297 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID CORN: Well, President
Obama is still
president until January 20, and
the world

12:44.330 --> 12:46.299 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
keeps turning.

12:46.332 --> 12:51.237 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, the Republicans wanted to
call his presidency
over last February, when he
nominated Merrick

12:51.270 --> 12:53.573 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Garland to the Supreme Court.

12:53.606 --> 12:56.909 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
The U.N. sanction vote came up.

12:56.943 --> 12:59.112 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It wasn't scheduled by Obama.

12:59.145 --> 13:03.816 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And a lot of people think he
should have responded
to the Russian hacking of the
U.S. elections

13:03.850 --> 13:04.917 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
weeks ago, months ago.

13:04.951 --> 13:06.986 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So these happened on his watch.

13:07.020 --> 13:09.689 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There's nothing wrong with him
dealing with
it.

13:09.722 --> 13:15.361 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Trump side now seems to be
whining that
he's violating the smooth
transition and trying

13:15.395 --> 13:17.196 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to delegitimize Trump.

13:17.230 --> 13:22.869 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But coming from Trump, who
pushed the racist
birth conspiracy theory for
years against

13:22.902 --> 13:26.873 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Barack Obama, I think Obama has
been very
much a gentleman.

13:26.906 --> 13:29.976 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And he has a lot of reason to
just not even
bother to deal with Trump.

13:30.009 --> 13:33.212 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: How different
is this from
previous presidents on their way
out?

13:33.246 --> 13:35.882 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Is it fairly traditional to
leave an exclamation
point at the end?

13:35.915 --> 13:37.750 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DAVID CORN: Well, it's kind of.

13:37.784 --> 13:42.922 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think, depending what is
happening -- when
George W. Bush left, he left
Barack Obama

13:42.955 --> 13:45.425 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
two raging wars.

13:45.458 --> 13:50.697 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the biggest fight he had was
inside his
own government about whether or
not to pardon

13:50.730 --> 13:52.565 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Scooter Libby.

13:52.598 --> 13:56.769 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he was sort of consumed
fighting with
Dick Cheney about that, and
didn't do a lot

13:56.803 --> 13:58.604 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I think externally.

13:58.638 --> 14:02.809 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think he was focused on
trying to, from
a national security perspective,
bring Obama

14:02.842 --> 14:07.513 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and his people up to speed, so
they could
take control of these wars.

14:07.547 --> 14:11.250 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Bill Clinton had the controversy
with pardons
when he was walking out the
door, Marc Rich

14:11.284 --> 14:14.420 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and others, that certainly
tarnished his reputation.

14:14.454 --> 14:17.857 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I think Obama is just doing
what he should
be doing at this point.

14:17.890 --> 14:21.494 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: David Brooks,
it almost
seems like there is a first 100
day strategy

14:21.527 --> 14:25.398 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and at the end of four or eight
years the
last hundred days, to do all the
things that

14:25.431 --> 14:27.834 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you wish you could have done,
but this is
on your way out.

14:27.867 --> 14:28.835 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID BROOKS: Yes.

14:28.868 --> 14:30.670 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That is not abnormal.

14:30.703 --> 14:32.839 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you look at regulations that
come out of
White Houses, even Republican
White Houses,

14:32.872 --> 14:36.709 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
there is a ton right at the end
as they try
to jam everything in at the end.

14:36.743 --> 14:38.611 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's reasonably standard.

14:38.644 --> 14:42.849 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But there certainly is a pattern
of administrations
that have good transitions,
George W. Bush

14:42.882 --> 14:46.719 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
to Barack Obama, and
administrations that
have really bad transitions, I
would say Eisenhower

14:46.753 --> 14:48.521 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to John F. Kennedy.

14:48.554 --> 14:51.290 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I would say this is beginning to
look like
a bad transition, as they begin
to argue even

14:51.324 --> 14:53.292 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
at the presidential level, which
is more or
less unprecedented.

14:53.326 --> 14:55.428 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Let's start
talking a little
bit about Russia.

14:55.461 --> 15:00.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Will the sanctions that we have
imposed keep
the Russian hackers out?

15:00.533 --> 15:02.068 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID BROOKS: No.

15:02.101 --> 15:03.069 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
No.

15:03.102 --> 15:04.504 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's so disproportionate.

15:04.537 --> 15:07.640 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
They interfered in our
elections, and we like
penalized a few of them.

15:07.673 --> 15:10.009 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Whatever they're doing
underground, we don't
know.

15:10.042 --> 15:11.744 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
No, this is going to be a big
issue.

15:11.778 --> 15:18.417 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I have to say the Obama --
the Trump position
is, A, mystifying, but, B,
doomed.

15:18.451 --> 15:21.254 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He has a nice little Putin
romance going on
right now.

15:21.287 --> 15:24.023 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think we're going to get out
the hankies,
because this is going to turn
into an ugly

15:24.056 --> 15:26.159 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
relationship within a year or
two.

15:26.192 --> 15:31.430 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The things that make them
similar -- their
machismo, their expansionary
braggadocio -- is

15:31.464 --> 15:34.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
going to turn them I think into
bitter and
dangerous enemies.

15:34.734 --> 15:37.937 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We will look back on this moment
where we
thought Putin and Trump were
sort of close

15:37.970 --> 15:42.408 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
as a moment of bitter irony,
when they get
into a schoolyard display
against each other,

15:42.441 --> 15:46.746 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
amping up each other's worst
tendencies and
putting the two countries in
some sort of

15:46.779 --> 15:48.114 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
scary position.

15:48.147 --> 15:49.682 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's just my feel of how
things are going
to get in the next year.

15:49.715 --> 15:52.752 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID CORN: That may be the
best-case scenario.

15:52.785 --> 15:55.788 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I don't necessarily see things
going that
way.

15:55.822 --> 16:01.460 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I still am mystified, to use
your word, about
why Trump is out there tweeting
praise of

16:01.494 --> 16:06.599 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Vladimir Putin these days, and
still kind
of denying and dismissing
whether the hacking

16:06.632 --> 16:08.534 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
happened or the seriousness of
it.

16:08.568 --> 16:12.371 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And people out there keep
asking, what is
behind this bromance?

16:12.405 --> 16:17.643 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Before the election, I reported
on a story
about a counterintelligence
officer from another

16:17.677 --> 16:23.549 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
service sending reports to the
FBI saying
that his sources in Russia were
saying that

16:23.583 --> 16:28.254 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Moscow tried for years to
cultivate and co-opt
Donald Trump.

16:28.287 --> 16:30.022 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I'm not saying that happened.

16:30.056 --> 16:34.660 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm saying I hope the FBI took a
strong look,
because it is really hard to
believe that

16:34.694 --> 16:41.567 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a president-elect would be so
callous in how
he approaches this issue and so
dismissive

16:41.601 --> 16:43.369 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of the seriousness of it.

16:43.402 --> 16:47.440 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so maybe he will turn on
Putin, as you
suggest, but maybe there is
something else

16:47.473 --> 16:53.045 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there in which he is enamored
with Putin for
some reason that we really don't
understand

16:53.079 --> 16:54.947 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
yet.

16:54.981 --> 16:57.116 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: What about the
president-elect's
position that we have got to
move on, these

16:57.149 --> 16:59.585 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are all essentially ploys to try
delegitimize
my win?

16:59.619 --> 17:04.190 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID CORN: Well, I think he
should be delegitimized
for many reasons.

17:04.223 --> 17:09.328 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And his response to this hacking
is also cause
for delegitimization.

17:09.362 --> 17:15.568 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But to say we should move on,
when the bedrock
of American democracy, the
sanctity of our

17:15.601 --> 17:18.971 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
elections, has been messed with,
just raises
suspicions.

17:19.005 --> 17:23.676 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It would be so easy for him to
say the obvious
thing: This is terrible.

17:23.709 --> 17:25.344 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We're going to look into it.

17:25.378 --> 17:28.247 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then we're going to try to
prevent this
from happening again in the
future.

17:28.281 --> 17:34.887 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But his denial of it happening
or its seriousness
shows that there is something
really amiss

17:34.921 --> 17:36.789 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
from his end of it.

17:36.822 --> 17:38.925 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: David Brooks,
what happens
in that conversation with
intelligence officials

17:38.958 --> 17:42.962 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that Donald Trump said he is
going to take
in order to get to the bottom of
this or get

17:42.995 --> 17:45.064 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to a common set of facts?

17:45.097 --> 17:48.801 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's already a fairly tense
relationship with
the intelligence community.

17:48.834 --> 17:51.170 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: Of course I don't
know what's
going on in that meeting on in
the mind of

17:51.203 --> 17:52.972 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Donald Trump.

17:53.005 --> 17:55.274 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I do know one of the things
President
Obama was struck by was how much
time he spent

17:55.308 --> 17:56.475 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
on cyber-security as president.

17:56.509 --> 17:58.945 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It was one of the big surprises
as president.

17:58.978 --> 18:02.481 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And one of the things he said
was that, in
the years ahead, the next
president will be

18:02.515 --> 18:03.983 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
spending even more time.

18:04.016 --> 18:06.886 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And cyber-security isn't a thing
that goes
away after this election.

18:06.919 --> 18:08.754 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's a constant flow.

18:08.788 --> 18:13.059 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And Russia has a very
sophisticated, advanced
attack on U.S. businesses and
U.S. government

18:13.092 --> 18:14.527 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and U.S. institutions.

18:14.560 --> 18:17.363 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it's not like Donald Trump
is going to
be walking away from this.

18:17.396 --> 18:20.166 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He will be spending a lot of
time on it, if
he's any sort of normal
president.

18:20.199 --> 18:21.968 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID CORN: Well, maybe, but we
don't know.

18:22.001 --> 18:27.340 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
He keeps dismissing the
seriousness and even
tweets out or puts a statement
saying, you

18:27.373 --> 18:29.709 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
know, computers, it's kind of
complicated.

18:29.742 --> 18:31.377 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You know, a lot of things
happen.

18:31.410 --> 18:36.949 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It remains to be seen what he is
serious about
on any policy level.

18:36.983 --> 18:41.487 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Well, speaking
of policy
level, one of the things that we
saw was that

18:41.520 --> 18:45.591 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the U.N. Security Council was
allowed to go
forward with the condemnation of
Israeli settlements,

18:45.624 --> 18:48.227 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that the United States didn't
use its veto
power.

18:48.260 --> 18:50.096 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Right move?

18:50.129 --> 18:55.201 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID CORN: I think it's a
policy that's very
defensible, in that, right now,
the settlements

18:55.234 --> 18:59.839 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are a complete obstacle or a
threat to a two-state
solution.

18:59.872 --> 19:06.012 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, I think Netanyahu and the
far right of
Israel don't believe in a
two-state solution,

19:06.045 --> 19:07.847 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and they just can't come out and
say it yet.

19:07.880 --> 19:12.918 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, Donald Trump's designated
ambassador
to Israel has said that quite
clearly.

19:12.952 --> 19:18.190 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But if there's no two-state
solution, then
Israel is on the path to being
an occupying

19:18.224 --> 19:21.861 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
nation without full political
rights for all
its inhabitants.

19:21.894 --> 19:26.165 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, you know, there have been
other Israeli
leaders who have talked about
the prospect

19:26.198 --> 19:28.701 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of a form of apartheid in
Israel.

19:28.734 --> 19:34.206 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I think the Obama position
and the majority
position of American Jews and a
lot of Americans

19:34.240 --> 19:36.809 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
is a two-state solution.

19:36.842 --> 19:38.377 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Settlements get in the way of
that.

19:38.411 --> 19:41.247 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If they're not stopped soon,
there is no prospect
for that type of solution.

19:41.280 --> 19:42.281 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: Now we disagree.

19:42.314 --> 19:45.051 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I think it's a completely
indefensible policy.

19:45.084 --> 19:47.686 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Settlements are an obstacle to
peace and to
a two-state solution.

19:47.720 --> 19:49.155 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
There's no question about that.

19:49.188 --> 19:52.391 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They are about the fifth or
sixth most important
obstacle right now.

19:52.425 --> 19:56.462 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The fact that there could be an
ISIS West
Bank, the fact that the
Palestinian government

19:56.495 --> 20:00.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in Gaza doesn't even acknowledge
Israel's
right to exist, the fact of
constant terror,

20:00.833 --> 20:05.037 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
delegitimization campaigns in
the Palestinian
schools, these are all much
bigger facts.

20:05.071 --> 20:10.976 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And for the Obama administration
to focus
on this one fact, almost, not to
the expense,

20:11.010 --> 20:15.114 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but to diminish some of the
others which are
much more important, is to cast
all the blame

20:15.147 --> 20:19.685 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on Israel and to take the U.N.
policy toward
Israel, which has been
longstanding, and sort

20:19.718 --> 20:21.587 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of surrender to it.

20:21.620 --> 20:26.325 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Netanyahu, Bibi Netanyahu, froze
the settlements
and offered to go toward a
two-state solution.

20:26.358 --> 20:28.027 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The Palestinians didn't take him
up on it.

20:28.060 --> 20:30.696 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Historically, we have had a
series of these
offers.

20:30.729 --> 20:33.999 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the settlements themselves
are not the
keystone here.

20:34.033 --> 20:38.671 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it seems to me myopic and
bizarre that
at the last moment, the Obama
administration

20:38.704 --> 20:43.976 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
would surrender the whole
balanced array of
policies that are obstacles to
peace and focus

20:44.009 --> 20:45.644 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
on the one that is most
detrimental to Israel.

20:45.678 --> 20:49.148 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID CORN: Well, I think John
Kerry's speech
was not just about settlements.

20:49.181 --> 20:53.586 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It was about the whole large
path to peace
and what's been happening to it.

20:53.619 --> 20:57.756 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it was one of the -- I think
one of the
most thorough policy statements
that you have

20:57.790 --> 21:00.826 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
seen from any secretary of state
on a contentious
issue.

21:00.860 --> 21:04.396 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, I think that it's not just
myopia.

21:04.430 --> 21:07.032 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The vote obviously was not
scheduled by the
administration.

21:07.066 --> 21:10.202 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I'm sure they would rather it
had not happened.

21:10.236 --> 21:14.874 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think they also wanted to
send a clear
signal, because they don't
believe Netanyahu

21:14.907 --> 21:18.310 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is serious about a two-state
solution.

21:18.344 --> 21:23.115 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the rapid expansion of the
settlements
is something that actually could
be stopped,

21:23.149 --> 21:27.820 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and may not even be up for
negotiation, but
would be a good unilateral move
on Israel's

21:27.853 --> 21:29.455 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
part.

21:29.488 --> 21:31.257 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: What about the
choice of
David Friedman as the
ambassador?

21:31.290 --> 21:33.192 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
What does that do to the
situation?

21:33.225 --> 21:36.428 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: Well, that just
shows how polarized
the whole situation has become,
because the

21:36.462 --> 21:40.032 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Obama administration has focused
the onus
on Israel and the settlements.

21:40.065 --> 21:45.504 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then the Trump potential
administration
apparently is pro-settlement,
and almost against

21:45.538 --> 21:47.306 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a two-state solution.

21:47.339 --> 21:53.045 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So we have got two polar
opposite Israel policies,
which really break what had been
a pretty

21:53.078 --> 21:56.282 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
decent bipartisan consensus that
we have got
to have a two-state solution, we
sort of know

21:56.315 --> 21:59.351 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
what the border is going to look
like, we
sort of know what East Jerusalem
is going

21:59.385 --> 22:01.153 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to look like.

22:01.187 --> 22:03.889 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And no administration has ever
said, as the
Obama administration sort of
implied, that

22:03.923 --> 22:08.327 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Israel wouldn't have access to
the Western
Wall, to the East Jerusalem.

22:08.360 --> 22:10.029 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And that was also in the
resolution.

22:10.062 --> 22:13.699 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And all administrations have not
really gone
on the U.N. train.

22:13.732 --> 22:17.369 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so what we're seeing is a
complete bifurcation
to two wrong Israeli policies.

22:17.403 --> 22:20.706 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
finally, staying
in the neighborhood, does it
matter that the

22:20.739 --> 22:26.178 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
U.S. is not a part of whatever
this cease-fire
in Syria is at the moment?

22:26.212 --> 22:30.649 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
DAVID BROOKS: I think it
matters, in that,
if you withdraw from the game,
you're out

22:30.683 --> 22:31.650 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of the game.

22:31.684 --> 22:33.252 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And we have withdrawn from the
game.

22:33.285 --> 22:34.753 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And we said Assad has to go.

22:34.787 --> 22:35.854 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
He's going to stay.

22:35.888 --> 22:37.323 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So we're out of the game.

22:37.356 --> 22:38.724 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they don't have to deal us
in when it
comes to finding a solution.

22:38.757 --> 22:39.959 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
But that was our choice.

22:39.992 --> 22:41.794 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That was our choice to withdraw
from that
particular game.

22:41.827 --> 22:46.232 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID CORN: We were behind two
cease-fires
this year, one in February that
lasted a few

22:46.265 --> 22:49.235 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
months, and one in September
that lasted about
a week.

22:49.268 --> 22:52.037 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have no idea how long this is
going to
last.

22:52.071 --> 22:57.343 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's a great possibility that
some on the
rebel side will start fighting
amongst themselves,

22:57.376 --> 23:03.716 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
because some of the rebel
groups, the more
fundamentalist, are not part of
the cease-fire.

23:03.749 --> 23:08.721 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, if there is anything that
stops the fighting
and stops the civilian
casualties, that's

23:08.754 --> 23:10.856 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a good thing now for a pause.

23:10.889 --> 23:13.993 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I'm not very optimistic this
is going
to last.

23:14.026 --> 23:17.696 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I do think John Kerry has
tried awfully
hard to work with Russia and
others to have

23:17.730 --> 23:19.732 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
a lasting, significant
cease-fire.

23:19.765 --> 23:22.534 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
David Corn of
"Mother Jones," David Brooks of
The New York

23:22.568 --> 23:28.240 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Times, David and David, thank
you very much.

23:28.274 --> 23:31.777 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DAVID CORN: Happy new year.

23:31.810 --> 23:34.647 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID BROOKS: Thank you.

23:34.680 --> 23:38.183 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Happy new
year.

23:38.217 --> 23:40.319 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Stay with us.

23:40.352 --> 23:44.757 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour":
another look
at the newest edition to the
National Mall:

23:44.790 --> 23:49.395 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the National Museum of African
American History
and Culture; and songwriter Josh
Ritter opens

23:49.428 --> 23:52.131 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
up about the doubt he feels on
stage.

23:52.164 --> 23:57.870 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But first: a broader look at
music and some
of the best work of this past
year.

23:57.903 --> 24:02.908 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As we say goodbye to 2016, we
also finish
our week-long series on the best
of arts.

24:02.941 --> 24:04.743 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown is our guide once
again.

24:04.777 --> 24:08.147 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Of all the
popular art forms
we have talked about this week,
delving into

24:08.180 --> 24:13.352 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the huge and diverse world of
music necessarily
means touching on just a slice
of the large

24:13.385 --> 24:15.054 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
pie.

24:15.087 --> 24:18.324 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Two music critics are here to
help us with
some of their own best of the
year.

24:18.357 --> 24:22.361 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Ann Powers of NPR and Mikael
Wood of The Los
Angeles Times.

24:22.394 --> 24:23.796 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Welcome to both of you.

24:23.829 --> 24:27.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Ann, let's just start with -- a
few albums
really dominated the year.

24:27.366 --> 24:28.967 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We might as well start there.

24:29.001 --> 24:30.736 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ANN POWERS, NPR: Absolutely.

24:30.769 --> 24:37.376 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, Beyonce's "Lemonade" was a
multimedia
phenomenon with the visual side,
a wonderful

24:37.409 --> 24:50.923 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
album and people talked about it
all year,
very political album.

24:50.956 --> 24:56.662 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Right next to that was David
Bowie's "Blackstar"
as equally lauded and
celebrated.

24:56.695 --> 24:59.031 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Of course, we lost David Bowie
this year.

24:59.064 --> 25:04.503 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So it was an interesting mix of
a young artist
at the top of her game and an
elder making

25:04.536 --> 25:07.072 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a final statement.

25:07.106 --> 25:16.048 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Mikael Wood,
let's start to
fill out your list here.

25:16.081 --> 25:18.884 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Give us a few of your -- what
stood out for
you.

25:18.917 --> 25:22.221 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MIKAEL WOOD, The Los Angeles
Times: Beyonce
and Bowie are both on my list.

25:22.254 --> 25:26.959 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You have also got the young
country singer
Maren Morris, who was doing a
lot of interesting

25:26.992 --> 25:30.929 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
things, sort of taking country
into an old-fashioned
way, but also making it very
contemporary

25:30.963 --> 25:35.901 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
at the same time.

25:35.934 --> 25:42.608 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You had a couple of great
hip-hop records
from Kanye West, who everybody
knows, of course,

25:42.641 --> 25:48.380 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but a younger rapper too from
Chicago called
Chance the Rapper, who made a
sort of gospel

25:48.414 --> 25:54.353 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
rap record that's very personal,
but also
sort of clearly situated in his
hometown and

25:54.386 --> 25:59.091 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
all of its various struggles,
really interesting
record.

25:59.124 --> 26:13.605 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right, so,
Ann, I made
you start with the ones
everybody knows.

26:13.639 --> 26:16.809 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But fill out a little more of
your top five
list or so.

26:16.842 --> 26:23.115 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANN POWERS: Well, speaking of
country singers,
there's a wonderful young singer
out of Nashville,

26:23.148 --> 26:28.887 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Margo Price, who made a very
traditional country
record called "Midwest Farmer's
Daughter,"

26:28.921 --> 26:31.890 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
with contemporary verb and
voice.

26:31.924 --> 26:33.725 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that's one of my favorites
of the year.

26:33.759 --> 26:36.495 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: That has a good
title, too,
right, "Midwest Farmer's
Daughter."

26:36.528 --> 26:37.496 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
ANN POWERS: Yes.

26:37.529 --> 26:38.797 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
She is a Midwest farmer's
daughter.

26:38.831 --> 26:41.934 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And Jack White's record label
Third Man put
it out.

26:41.967 --> 26:53.045 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, it is country and cool.

26:53.078 --> 26:56.081 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I really love Chance the Rapper,
which Mikael
mentioned.

26:56.114 --> 27:02.754 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Also, Beyonce's sister Solange
Knowles released
a very beautiful, introspective
album called

27:02.788 --> 27:08.093 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
"A Seat at the Table" that again
reflected
the political moment in a very
different way.

27:08.126 --> 27:13.799 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If Beyonce was forceful and out
there, Solange
was quiet and thinking and
meditating and

27:13.832 --> 27:15.200 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
dreaming.

27:15.234 --> 27:20.873 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that was actually NPR
Music's number one
record of the year.

27:20.906 --> 27:33.685 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Well, Mikael, so
we're talking.

27:33.719 --> 27:35.220 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I want to bring in performances.

27:35.254 --> 27:37.089 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We're talking mostly about
recordings.

27:37.122 --> 27:39.925 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
