people really

36:47.072 --> 36:48.873 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
care.

36:48.907 --> 36:52.277 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are times I will walk in
an airport
and people will just sort of
give me the thumbs

36:52.310 --> 36:56.948 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
up, or I will walk down the
street and church
ladies will come to me and say
they're praying

36:56.981 --> 36:58.817 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
for me.

36:58.850 --> 37:02.387 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I think the fact that this
means so much
to so many people has been the
biggest surprise

37:02.420 --> 37:04.355 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
for me.

37:04.389 --> 37:09.294 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: As with other
Smithsonian museums,
one building cannot begin to
hold its collection.

37:09.327 --> 37:14.332 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Conservator Antje Neumann has
helped preserve
the collection at the museum's
facility in

37:14.365 --> 37:16.167 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a Washington suburb.

37:16.201 --> 37:17.936 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANTJE NEUMANN, Conservator,
National Museum
of African American History and
Culture: There's

37:17.969 --> 37:23.208 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
always the balance between
preservation and
exhibition, and allowing the
public to see

37:23.241 --> 37:28.446 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the national treasures, and then
also balancing
that with preserving it for
future generations.

37:28.480 --> 37:35.019 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's lovely to have a place to
highlight the
struggles, the causes and the
progression

37:35.053 --> 37:38.990 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
that many people and the
contributions many
people have done in this
country.

37:39.023 --> 37:44.028 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: It falls to Neumann
to repair
Shaquille O'Neal's size 20 shoe,
to prepare

37:44.062 --> 37:50.735 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a stool from Muhammad Ali's gym,
to restore
worn pages of the first book of
black poetry,

37:50.768 --> 37:54.873 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and to spiff up funk singer
Bootsy Collins'
bright yellow leather costume.

37:54.906 --> 37:59.511 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANTJE NEUMANN: It just needs a
bit -- a little
bit of cleaning in order to make
it ready

37:59.544 --> 38:03.348 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for presentation, as it has been
used a lot
on stage.

38:03.381 --> 38:08.286 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Collins' outfit
occupies a place
of honor inside the new
building, which is

38:08.319 --> 38:10.155 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a work of art itself.

38:10.188 --> 38:17.428 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The corona, the signature
exterior feature,
is made of 230 tons of
bronze-colored aluminum

38:17.462 --> 38:20.698 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
panels, 3,600 in all.

38:20.732 --> 38:24.102 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Lead architect Phil Freelon
oversaw the building's
striking design.

38:24.135 --> 38:28.773 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PHIL FREELON, Lead Architect:
Many of the
buildings on the Mall are
marble, granite,

38:28.806 --> 38:31.242 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
concrete, lighter in color.

38:31.276 --> 38:34.746 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This building has a variation in
how it appears.

38:34.779 --> 38:39.551 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, on certain days, in certain
lighting conditions,
it can be very vibrant and
bright.

38:39.584 --> 38:43.755 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And other times of the day or in
the evening,
it is darker.

38:43.788 --> 38:48.993 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So there is this interesting
dynamic of changing
appearance of the building.

38:49.027 --> 38:54.832 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Within view, the
Washington Monument
and even a glimpse of the White
House, which

38:54.866 --> 38:59.404 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Michelle Obama famously noted
was itself built
by slaves.

38:59.437 --> 39:04.108 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Bunch says this makes race an
integral part
of the American experience.

39:04.142 --> 39:09.047 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, in this country, we are so
nervous about
talking about race, about
engaging.

39:09.080 --> 39:13.351 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
We keep having national
conversations about
race, and it seems that this
building itself

39:13.384 --> 39:15.453 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
is a big conversation.

39:15.486 --> 39:19.390 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Do you -- did you encounter
along the way
any resistance to the notion
that we talk

39:19.424 --> 39:21.826 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
about Americans only by race?

39:21.859 --> 39:29.701 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LONNIE BUNCH: I think there was
fear that
we would be a place that might
be divisive,

39:29.734 --> 39:34.505 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that people wouldn't want to
talk about race,
and that we would force them to
talk about

39:34.539 --> 39:36.341 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
race.

39:36.374 --> 39:41.980 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think there was a great
concern that, would
this just be a museum by black
people for

39:42.013 --> 39:43.781 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
black people?

39:43.815 --> 39:48.453 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think we had to counter
that, both by
the kind of stories we told, by
the way we

39:48.486 --> 39:53.358 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
tried to say, this is a story of
America through
an African-American lens.

39:53.391 --> 39:57.629 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Joyce Bailey's
mother could not
have foreseen this day, but she
did see the

39:57.662 --> 40:00.598 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
value of preserving black
history.

40:00.632 --> 40:07.038 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Lois Alexander passed away in
2007, leaving
her daughter with a window into
history.

40:07.071 --> 40:09.807 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But didn't you feel a little
emotional about
letting it go?

40:09.841 --> 40:15.179 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOYCE BAILEY: I was very happy
about letting
it go, because I knew my
mother's legacy would

40:15.213 --> 40:16.180 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
continue.

40:16.214 --> 40:18.950 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Curators think about
legacy too.

40:18.983 --> 40:20.852 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Lonnie Bunch is still looking
ahead.

40:20.885 --> 40:25.423 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LONNIE BUNCH: I want to make
sure that curators
50 years from now can tell the
story of today,

40:25.456 --> 40:27.292 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
if that's what they want to
tell.

40:27.325 --> 40:33.364 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I hope this museum will
continue to evolve,
continue to change, because it
really has

40:33.398 --> 40:38.503 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to be a place that is the great
convener,
that can bring anybody and
everybody into

40:38.536 --> 40:40.705 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a conversation around race.

40:40.738 --> 40:53.084 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: From groundbreaking
in 2012 to
open doors this week, America
preserved, America

40:53.117 --> 40:56.321 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
celebrated, right in the
nation's front yard.

40:56.354 --> 41:02.160 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The story
originally aired
in September, one of Gwen's
favorites and

41:02.193 --> 41:12.303 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
one of our favorite stories from
2016.

41:12.303 --> 41:17.508 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
one of our favorite stories from
2016.

41:17.542 --> 41:23.381 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We looked at the best books of
2016 earlier
this week, and both our guests
agreed a standout

41:23.414 --> 41:29.087 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this year was a book that
examined the cascading
impact poverty has on housing.

41:29.120 --> 41:30.855 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Jeff is back with this reprise.

41:30.888 --> 41:34.692 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Every year in
this country,
families are evicted from their
homes, not

41:34.726 --> 41:39.430 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
by the tens of thousands or by
the hundreds
of thousands, but by the
millions, that from

41:39.464 --> 41:44.302 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a new book that explores a huge,
but little
discussed phenomenon in America
today.

41:44.335 --> 41:49.474 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
"Evicted: Poverty and Profit in
the American
City" follows the lives of eight
Milwaukee

41:49.507 --> 41:50.875 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
families, black and white.

41:50.908 --> 41:54.579 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Author Matthew Desmond lived
among them in
2008 to 2009.

41:54.612 --> 42:00.284 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's a sociologist, a professor
at Harvard
and a winner of a MacArthur
Fellowship last

42:00.318 --> 42:01.285 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
year.

42:01.319 --> 42:03.087 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And welcome to you.

42:03.121 --> 42:04.922 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MATTHEW DESMOND, Author,
"Evicted: Poverty
and Profit in the American
City": Thank you.

42:04.956 --> 42:06.991 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Eviction is far
more prevalent
than most people think and far
less part of

42:07.024 --> 42:09.660 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the discussion around poverty in
this country.

42:09.694 --> 42:11.129 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Why do you think that's the
case?

42:11.162 --> 42:13.064 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MATTHEW DESMOND: I think we
focus a lot on
jobs.

42:13.097 --> 42:16.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
We focus a lot on mass
incarceration and welfare
reform.

42:16.334 --> 42:19.504 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But housing has been left out of
the debate
a little bit.

42:19.537 --> 42:23.708 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have focused on public
housing, and we
have focused on neighborhoods,
but the private

42:23.741 --> 42:28.980 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
rental market, where a vast
majority of low-income
families are living, has been
largely overlooked.

42:29.013 --> 42:33.151 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But here is this market that's
taking most
of what low-income families are
making.

42:33.184 --> 42:34.152 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
There's a...

42:34.185 --> 42:35.420 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

42:35.453 --> 42:36.187 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: An incredible
amount, percentage
of income.

42:36.220 --> 42:37.221 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I mean, that's really striking.

42:37.255 --> 42:38.222 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MATTHEW DESMOND: Yes.

42:38.256 --> 42:39.223 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Yes.

42:39.257 --> 42:40.992 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Seventy, 80, 90
percent.

42:41.025 --> 42:42.760 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MATTHEW DESMOND: Yes, that's
what I saw when
I was living with families in
Milwaukee.

42:42.794 --> 42:46.063 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we reached a point today
that we know
that the majority of low-income
renters are

42:46.097 --> 42:49.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
paying most of what they have
just on rent
and to keep the lights on.

42:49.734 --> 42:51.936 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: I said you
followed eight families.

42:51.969 --> 42:56.841 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Pick one person to explain sort
of how people
fall into this and how hard it
is to get out

42:56.874 --> 42:57.842 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
of it.

42:57.875 --> 42:58.843 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MATTHEW DESMOND: Yes, yes.

42:58.876 --> 42:59.844 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I'm thinking of Arlene.

42:59.877 --> 43:00.845 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You know, Arlene was a single
mom.

43:00.878 --> 43:02.747 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
She had two young boys.

43:02.780 --> 43:05.616 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when I met her, she was
living in a pretty
run-down apartment in a
low-income neighborhood

43:05.650 --> 43:09.187 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and giving 88 percent of her
income on rent.

43:09.220 --> 43:11.355 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And she was facing terrible
choices.

43:11.389 --> 43:14.225 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You know, should I buy food or
pay the rent?

43:14.258 --> 43:17.128 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Should I contribute some money
to the funeral
or pay the rent?

43:17.161 --> 43:21.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And someone like Arlene,
eviction isn't necessarily
the result of irresponsibility.

43:21.966 --> 43:23.935 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's more inevitable.

43:23.968 --> 43:27.371 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: They're making
some bad choices,
but you're showing how it's a
kind of -- almost

43:27.405 --> 43:30.908 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a vicious cycle, right, of the
eviction playing
into those choices.

43:30.942 --> 43:34.612 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MATTHEW DESMOND: If you're
someone like Arlene
that's paying almost everything
you have to

43:34.645 --> 43:38.783 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the landlord, a very small
divergence can
invite an eviction.

43:38.816 --> 43:43.254 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The book opens with her
14-year-old hitting
a car with a snowball, you know,
and the man

43:43.287 --> 43:47.024 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
jumping out, kicking in the
door, and that
causing the landlord to evict
the family.

43:47.058 --> 43:49.227 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Was that a bad choice?

43:49.260 --> 43:51.028 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Eviction isn't just a condition
of poverty.

43:51.062 --> 43:52.697 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's also a cause of it.

43:52.730 --> 43:54.465 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's making things worse.

43:54.499 --> 43:57.802 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You show the
rawness of what
an eviction -- I mean, you
capture what it

43:57.835 --> 43:58.803 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
looks like.

43:58.836 --> 43:59.804 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MATTHEW DESMOND: Yes.

43:59.837 --> 44:01.706 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Describe that.

44:01.739 --> 44:04.976 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, take an example of what
perhaps struck
you even the first time you
actually saw what

44:05.009 --> 44:08.246 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that's like, when you see
everything thrown
out of the house.

44:08.279 --> 44:11.516 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MATTHEW DESMOND: I remember
seeing Arlene
get evicted in early January.

44:11.549 --> 44:14.051 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It was the coldest day on record
in Milwaukee.

44:14.085 --> 44:20.024 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, the weathermen said it
would be
40 degrees below with the
windchill.

44:20.057 --> 44:27.164 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And seeing a family's things
piled on a curb,
seeing children forced from
their homes, seeing

44:27.198 --> 44:31.269 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the things taken by movers and
put in bonded
storage, and often, kind of,
taken to the

44:31.302 --> 44:36.340 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
dump when families can't keep up
with those
payments, it's a violent act,
eviction.

44:36.374 --> 44:37.708 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It can leave a deep mark.

44:37.742 --> 44:41.512 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we know it leaves a mark on
families that
experience it.

44:41.546 --> 44:46.417 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: It leaves a mark
in terms of,
obviously, their budget, but a
psychological

44:46.450 --> 44:47.952 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
mark is what you're really
documenting.

44:47.985 --> 44:49.353 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MATTHEW DESMOND: Yes, that's
absolutely right.

44:49.387 --> 44:51.289 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It affects your spirit.

44:51.322 --> 44:55.459 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, we know that mothers
who are evicted,
two years later have higher
rates of depression.

44:55.493 --> 45:01.065 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We know that suicides attributed
to evictions
or foreclosures doubled between
2005 and 2010.

45:01.098 --> 45:05.703 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, eviction not only causes you
to lose your
home and your things and your
community, but

45:05.736 --> 45:09.407 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
also has deep effects on the way
you see yourself
and your mental health.

45:09.440 --> 45:14.011 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You also got a
couple of landlords
to talk to you and let you
follow them around.

45:14.045 --> 45:15.780 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MATTHEW DESMOND: I thought that
was crucial.

45:15.813 --> 45:19.984 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I thought, if I really wanted to
understand
how housing is causing poverty
in America,

45:20.017 --> 45:21.552 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I needed to get landlords'
perspectives.

45:21.586 --> 45:24.488 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I didn't understand why they
evicted me, but
not you.

45:24.522 --> 45:26.524 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I needed to understand what
makes them tick.

45:26.557 --> 45:29.427 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And there is a business model at
the bottom
of the market.

45:29.460 --> 45:33.431 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the one thing I found that
surprised me
was that landlords that are
operating in very

45:33.464 --> 45:37.368 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
poor neighborhoods can make a
decent profit,
an extreme profit in some cases.

45:37.401 --> 45:40.104 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The eviction
becomes part of
the profit, right?

45:40.137 --> 45:45.476 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, it can be -- it can be
beneficial
to them to evict somebody, bring
somebody

45:45.509 --> 45:48.679 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
else in, not put much into the
actual rental
property.

45:48.713 --> 45:50.448 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MATTHEW DESMOND: That's right.

45:50.481 --> 45:53.918 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And for some landlords, eviction
is costly,
and it does take money, but, for
others, it's

45:53.951 --> 45:55.653 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
part of the business model.

45:55.686 --> 46:00.992 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the short answer to that is,
it's more
efficient to evict a family than
to keep up

